
** Blocking Queue: -Blocking queue interface represents a queue which is Thread safe to put elements into,
                   and take elements out of form.
           Usage:- Typically used in producer-consumer pattern — one thread produces objects and puts into queue,
                   another thread consumes (takes out) from the same queue. Both threads don't need to worry about
                   synchronization, BlockingQueue handles it internally.

=============================================================================================================================                  


** // Step 1: Create a BlockingQueue with capacity 5

    BlockingQueue<String> queue = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(5);

    // Step 2: Producer thread — puts items into queue
    Thread producer = new Thread(() -> {
        try {
            queue.put("Order-1");    // if queue full, this line will BLOCK until space available
            queue.put("Order-2");
            queue.put("Order-3");
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }
    });


 ** // Step 3: Consumer thread — takes items from queue
    Thread consumer = new Thread(() -> {
        try {
            String item = queue.take();  // if queue empty, this line will BLOCK until item available
            System.out.println("Consumed: " + item);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }
    });


** // Step 4: Start both threads
    producer.start();
    consumer.start();


**  Key Methods:
    queue.put(item)          -> blocks if queue is full, waits until space available
    queue.take()             -> blocks if queue is empty, waits until item available
    queue.offer(item)        -> returns false immediately if queue is full (non-blocking)
    queue.offer(item, 5, TimeUnit.SECONDS)  -> waits 5 sec, then returns false if still full
    queue.poll()             -> returns null immediately if queue is empty (non-blocking)
    queue.poll(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS)         -> waits 5 sec, then returns null if still empty
    queue.size()             -> current number of items in queue
    queue.remainingCapacity() -> how many more items can fit                      